{{ill|Matsumae Gokoku Shrine|simple|ja|松前護國神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsumae Gokoku Shrine|qq=|qid=Q5287|1=Japanese language}} (松前護國神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}.  It is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]], or a shrine dedicated to war dead.{{Efn|Is this [[WP:BLUE]] considering that the shrine is literally named as such?}} Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|qid=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|qid=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha|1=Shōkonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

Matsumae Gokoku Shrine is a Shinto shrine located in Matsumae, Hokkaido, Japan. Gokoku shrines, originally known as Shokonsha, were established during the Meiji Restoration to honor individuals who died in wars, serving as local branches of the central Yasukuni Shrine in Tokyo. <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gokoku_Shrines</ref>

Situated near Matsumae Castle, the northernmost castle in Japan, Matsumae Gokoku Shrine is part of a historic area that includes other notable sites such as Matsumae Shrine and the Buddhist temple Ryūun-in. <ref>https://mapcarta.com/W647365281</ref>

Visitors to Matsumae Gokoku Shrine can explore the rich history of the region, with the shrine serving as a place of remembrance for those who sacrificed their lives in service to the nation. The surrounding area offers a glimpse into Japan's feudal past, with Matsumae Castle and other cultural landmarks nearby.

For those interested in visiting, the shrine is accessible by a short walk from the Matsuki bus stop. The address is 145 Matsushiro, Matsumae-chō, Matsumae-gun, Hokkaido. <ref>https://map.uu-hokkaido.jp/e/matsumae-shrine/</ref>

Please note that information about Matsumae Gokoku Shrine is limited, and visitors are encouraged to explore the site in person to fully appreciate its historical and cultural significance

